The article states that pursuant to section 404 of the Child Soldiers Prevention Act of 2008, the President of the United States, Joseph R. Biden Jr., has determined that it is in the national interest to waive the application of the prohibition in section 404(a) of the act with respect to certain countries. The countries include Iraq, Nigeria, Pakistan, and Turkey. The waiver allows for the provision of International Military Education and Training (IMET) and Peacekeeping Operations (PKO) assistance. The waiver also applies to the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Libya, Somalia, Yemen, and South Sudan, but with certain limitations. The President has certified that the governments of these countries are taking effective and continuing steps to address the problem of child soldiers. The determination will be submitted to Congress and published in the Federal Register.